voice_to_text: What if I told you that the best black fashion magazine ever created was a publication that hardly anyone got to see? Suede magazine was a joint venture between essence magazine and Time, Inc. And it launched in 2004 with a focus on luxurious fashion for women of color. However, it did not last very long. The first cover, which came out in September 2,004, featured Alicia Keys, the second cover saw Eve, the third was Zoe Saldana, and the fourth and final cover featured Tyra Banks. As well as these glamorous, well known names on the covers, the brands throughout were luxurious Chanel, YSL, Valentino, Elie, Saab, and throughout the magazine there were these beautiful illustrations and detailed editorials crafted by creative director Richard Christensen. The rest of the team included Suzanne Boyd as editor, Ying Chu as beauty director, Ian Hilton as editor at large, and Agnes Kamak as fashion, market, news and trends director. I was recently reminded of suede magazine's existence when I chatted to Andrea Lewis, the creator of the Netflix documentary series The Black Beauty Effect. It was supposed to be Essence's Millennial Girl magazine. It was four girl millennial millennial girls that were young at the time.
